data.content:
Here's the refactored test using TUnit's native `ThrowsException` assertion:

```csharp
using TUnit.Core;

public class OrderProcessorTests
{
    [Test]
    public async Task ProcessOrder_EmptyOrder_ThrowsInvalidOperation()
    {
        var processor = new OrderProcessor();

        var exception = await Assert.ThrowsAsync<InvalidOperationException>(
            () => processor.ProcessOrder(new Order()));

        await Assert.That(exception.Message).IsEqualTo("Order must contain at least one item");
    }
}
```

This verifies both the exception type (`InvalidOperationException`) and the message in an idiomatic way — `ThrowsAsync<T>` asserts the correct exception is thrown and returns it for further inspection.
